     <h1>How to Be A Parent NOW</h1> 
     <h2><strong>Learning to Live Out of the Loop</strong></h2> 
     <p style="text-align:left !important;">Parenting is a lifelong opportunity.&nbsp; The opportunities to nurture, teach, love and guide our&nbsp;<br> children never go away.&nbsp; Whether in diapers or driver’s education, our children needed us then and they will continue to need us in the future.</p> 
     <p style="text-align:justify;">At Westmont, your student will have a great deal of independence. That independence is a critical part of growing up. Your student will no longer make decisions based simply on your rules; they will instead make them based on their own values, ideas and perspectives. Don’t be surprised if their sense of independence overshadows their sense of obligation or accountability to you. Your inquiries may be misconstrued as interrogations, your sincere&nbsp; interest may be perceived as an intrusion. How do you adjust?</p> 
     <p style="text-align:justify;">The Parents Council is here to help you in that transition. As parents of Westmont students, the members of the Parents Council have a lot of experience with the transition that awaits you. Here are a few suggestions:</p> 
     <p style="text-align:justify;">• Check in, don’t check up.&nbsp; You want to know what is going on in your student’s life, but you need to make sure your curiosity does not seem like “checking up” on them.&nbsp; A good balance is through letters and e-mail. They are not intrusive and allow your student to respond at his or her own discretion.</p> 
     <p style="text-align:justify;">• Learn to listen.&nbsp;You might want to check on how studies are doing, or how things are working out with their roommate, but let your student lead the conversation.&nbsp; Listen and don’t slip into lecturing (they get enough of that in class!).</p> 
     <p style="text-align:justify;">• Give advice only when asked.&nbsp;Or if you absolutely must, ask if you can give them advice.&nbsp; Seeking out answers on their own is part of the learning process for all students. Your student may not come to you at first, but if you honor their independence, sooner or later, you will hear them ask, “What do you think I should do?”</p> 
     <p style="text-align:justify;">• Pray for them.&nbsp;&nbsp;While that seems obvious, it can never be said often enough.&nbsp; Your student needs your prayers.&nbsp; And if they know that you are praying for them, they are much more likely to be open and honest with you about their prayer needs.</p> 
     <p style="text-align:justify;">• Let your student live under your roof, but not under your thumb.&nbsp;&nbsp;The hardest adjustment will be when your child returns home.&nbsp; You might want them to abide by the same rules they had in high school, but your child has been living in a different paradigm.&nbsp; It might be helpful to emphasize that courtesy and respect dictate that you be advised of their comings and goings rather than trying to institute the old rules.</p> 
     <p style="text-align:justify;">• Finally, look for ways to embrace the growth that comes as a result of your student’s independence.&nbsp;Celebrate the maturity, the critical thinking skills, the curiosity, and the spiritual development that will become more obvious in your student.&nbsp; Rather than seeing their independence as a threat to your parental role, view it as a gift that enhances the opportunity to love your child even more.</p> 
     <p style="text-align:justify;">The Parents Council hopes that you find these suggestions helpful.&nbsp; There are many other ideas to share, and the members of the Parents Council would love to talk with you if you have questions or ideas.&nbsp; No one person has all the answers, and no one parenting method is right for each situation, but the value of experience should never be hidden. We all share the same goal of wanting the best for our student. So let’s share ideas, ask questions, and encourage each other in our role as parents.</p> 
     <p>&nbsp; </p> 
